# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: variant-calling-gatk
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:variant-calling-gatk/base-calling] Currently basecalling is commonly handled by on-instrument software, such as the proprietary Real-Time Analysis (RTA) pipeline, which is highly integrated and updated with each platform release.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/base-calling] Base callers for Nanopore sequencing like Guppy or Dorado, use neural networks trained on current signals obtained from accurate sequencing data.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/base-calling] Base calling can be assessed by two metrics, read accuracy and consensus accuracy.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/base-calling] Read accuracy refers to the called base's accuracy to a known reference.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/base-calling] Consensus accuracy refers to how accurate a consensus sequence is compared to overlapping reads from the same genetic locus.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] The GATK is the industry standard for identifying SNPs and indels in germline DNA and RNAseq data.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] Its scope is now expanding to include somatic short variant calling, and to tackle copy number (CNV) and structural variation (SV).
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] In addition to the variant callers themselves, the GATK also includes many utilities to perform related tasks such as processing and quality control of high-throughput sequencing data, and bundles the popular Picard toolkit.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] These tools were primarily designed to process exomes and whole genomes generated with Illumina sequencing technology, but they can be adapted to handle a variety of other technologies and experimental designs.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] And although it was originally developed for human genetics, the GATK has since evolved to handle genome data from any organism, with any level of ploidy.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] When you're isolating DNA in the lab, you don't treat the work like isolated, disconnected tasks.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] Every task is a step in a well-documented protocol, carefully developed to optimize yield, purity and to ensure reproducibility as well as consistency across all samples and experiments.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] We believe working with the sequencing data should be treated in the same thorough manner.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] That's why GATK comes with complete reads-to-results Best Practices workflow recommendations, battle-tested in production at the Broad Institute and optimized to produce the most accurate results with the most computational efficiency.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] GATK4 includes Best Practices workflows for all major classes of variants for genomic analysis in gene panels, exomes and whole genomes.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] In addition to the industry standard GATK Best Practices workflow for germline short variant discovery, GATK4 offers Best Practices workflows for somatic short variants, somatic and germline copy number variants, and structural variation discovery tools are in active development.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] The GATK is designed to run on Linux and other POSIX-compatible platforms, which includes MacOS X.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] The major system requirement is Java 1.8; some tools have additional R or Python dependencies.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] We recommend using Docker containers for ease of deployment; an official docker container is available on Dockerhub.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] If you prefer to run the software directly, see the Download section for download and installation instructions.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] In addition to supporting traditional compute environments such as local clusters, the next generation of GATK tools has been engineered to also play well with cloud environments and to leverage Spark architectures wherever possible.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] See the Pipelining Options documentation for more information on supported platforms and available optimizations.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] At the heart of the GATK is an industrial-strength infrastructure and engine that handle data access, conversion and traversal, as well as high-performance computing features.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] This includes parallelization using Apache Spark and optimized usage of cloud infrastructure.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] On top of that lives a rich ecosystem of specialized tools that you can use out of the box, individually or chained into scripted workflows, to perform anything from simple data diagnostics to complex reads-to-variants analyses.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] See the Tool Docs for a complete list of tools and their capabilities.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] Starting in GATK4, the GATK executable also bundles the popular Picard toolkit for manipulation and quality control of high-throughput sequencing data.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] All Picard tools are now available directly from the GATK command-line, with a harmonized command syntax and consolidated user guide.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] As described on Github, it is a permissive license similar to the BSD 2-Clause License, but with a 3rd clause that prohibits others from using the name of the project or its contributors to promote derived products without written consent.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] The full text of the license can be viewed here.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] The GATK has a reputation for being wicked complicated, and it's not entirely undeserved.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] With great power comes great responsibility complexity...
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] The toolkit comes with extensive documentation about the tools themselves, the underlying algorithms, and a lot of information about how to apply them to your data for best results.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] For the major use cases, we provide best-practice workflow recommendations that describe how to chain the tools together into processing and analysis pipelines.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] This documentation is further enriched by a regularly updated collection of frequently asked questions and troubleshooting recommendations, a glossary of technical terms, and tutorials that explain step by step how to run the tools and apply our workflow recommendations.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] Be sure to check out the presentations from our recurring workshop series.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] In addition to the slide decks, we provide recordings of the workshops that we hold at the Broad; you can view them on the Broad website or on the Broad education channels on YouTube and iTunesU.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] Finally, if you've exhausted all these avenues and still haven't found the answer to your question, check out the forum!
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] You may find that others have run into the same problem and that the solution has already been posted.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] If not, let us know and we'll do our best to address your problems quickly and accurately.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] If something's not clearly documented, we'll answer your question and improve the docs accordingly.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/hc-en-us] If you think you found a bug, we'll track it down and fix it.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] In coding regions of the genome, unless the length of an indel is a multiple of 3, it will produce a frameshift mutation.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] For example, a common microindel which results in a frameshift causes Bloom syndrome in the Jewish or Japanese population.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] Indels can be contrasted with a **point mutation**.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] An indel inserts or deletes nucleotides from a sequence, while a point mutation is a form of substitution that *replaces* one of the nucleotides without changing the overall number in the DNA.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] Indels can also be contrasted with Tandem Base Mutations (TBM), which may result from fundamentally different mechanisms.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] A TBM is defined as a substitution at adjacent nucleotides (primarily substitutions at two adjacent nucleotides, but substitutions at three adjacent nucleotides have been observed).
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] Indels, being either insertions, or deletions, can be used as genetic markers in natural populations, especially in phylogenetic studies.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] It has been shown that genomic regions with multiple indels can also be used for species-identification procedures.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] An indel change of a single base pair in the coding part of an mRNA results in a frameshift during mRNA translation that could lead to an inappropriate (premature) stop codon in a different frame.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] Indels that are not multiples of 3 are particularly uncommon in coding regions but relatively common in non-coding regions.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] There are approximately 192-280 frameshifting indels in each person.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] Indels are likely to represent between 16% and 25% of all sequence polymorphisms in humans.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] In most known genomes, including humans, indel frequency tends to be markedly lower than that of single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNP), except near highly repetitive regions, including homopolymers and microsatellites.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] The term "indel" has been co-opted in recent years by genome scientists for use in the sense described above.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] This is a change from its original use and meaning, which arose from systematics.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] In systematics, researchers could find differences between sequences, such as from two different species.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] But it was impossible to infer if one species lost the sequence or the other species gained it.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] For example, species *A* has a run of 4 G nucleotides at a locus and species *B* has 5 G's at the same locus.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] If the mode of selection is unknown, one can not tell if species A lost one G (a "deletion" event") or species B gained one G (an "insertion" event).
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] When one cannot infer the phylogenetic direction of the sequence change, the sequence change event is referred to as an "indel".
[src:variant-calling-gatk/indel] Using passenger-immunoglobulin mouse models, a study found that the most prevalent indel events are the activation-induced cytidine deaminase (AID)-dependent ±1-base pair (bp) indels, which can lead to deleterious outcomes, whereas longer in-frame indels were rare outcomes.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] In genetics and bioinformatics, a **single-nucleotide polymorphism** (**SNP** /snɪp/; plural **SNPs** /snɪps/) is a germline substitution of a single nucleotide at a specific position in the genome.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Although certain definitions require the substitution to be present in a sufficiently large fraction of the population (e.g.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] 1% or more), many publications do not apply such a frequency threshold.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] For example, a G nucleotide present at a specific location in a reference genome may be replaced by an A in a minority of individuals.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The two possible nucleotide variations of this SNP – G or A – are called alleles.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs can help explain differences in susceptibility to a wide range of diseases across a population.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] For example, a common SNP in the CFH gene is associated with increased risk of age-related macular degeneration.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Differences in the severity of an illness or response to treatments may also be manifestations of genetic variations caused by SNPs.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] For example, two common SNPs in the *APOE* gene, rs429358 and rs7412, lead to three major APO-E alleles with different associated risks for development of Alzheimer's disease and age at onset of the disease.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Single nucleotide substitutions with an allele frequency of less than 1% are sometimes called single-nucleotide variants.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] "Variant" may also be used as a general term for any single nucleotide change in a DNA sequence, encompassing both common SNPs and rare mutations, whether germline or somatic.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The term single-nucleotide variant has therefore been used to refer to point mutations found in cancer cells.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] DNA variants must also commonly be taken into consideration in molecular diagnostics applications such as designing PCR primers to detect viruses, in which the viral RNA or DNA sample may contain single-nucleotide variants.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] However, this nomenclature uses arbitrary distinctions (such as an allele frequency of 1%) and is not used consistently across all fields; the resulting disagreement has prompted calls for a more consistent framework for naming differences in DNA sequences between two samples.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Single-nucleotide polymorphisms may fall within coding sequences of genes, non-coding regions of genes, or in the intergenic regions (regions between genes).
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs within a coding sequence do not necessarily change the amino acid sequence of the protein that is produced, due to degeneracy of the genetic code.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs in the coding region are of two types: synonymous SNPs and nonsynonymous SNPs.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Synonymous SNPs do not affect the protein sequence, while nonsynonymous SNPs change the amino acid sequence of protein.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs that are not in protein-coding regions may still affect gene splicing, transcription factor binding, messenger RNA degradation, or the sequence of noncoding RNA.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Gene expression affected by this type of SNP is referred to as an eSNP (expression SNP) and may be upstream or downstream from the gene.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] More than 600 million SNPs have been identified across the human genome in the world's population.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] A typical genome differs from the reference human genome at 4–5 million sites, most of which (more than 99.9%) consist of SNPs and short indels.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The genomic distribution of SNPs is not homogenous; SNPs occur in non-coding regions more frequently than in coding regions or, in general, where natural selection is acting and "fixing" the allele (eliminating other variants) of the SNP that constitutes the most favorable genetic adaptation.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Other factors, like genetic recombination and mutation rate, can also determine SNP density.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNP density can be predicted by the presence of microsatellites: AT microsatellites in particular are potent predictors of SNP density, with long (AT)(n) repeat tracts tending to be found in regions of significantly reduced SNP density and low GC content.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Since there are variations between human populations, a SNP allele that is common in one geographical or ethnic group may be rarer in another.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] However, this pattern of variation is relatively rare; in a global sample of 67.3 million SNPs, the Human Genome Diversity Project "found no such private variants that are fixed in a given continent or major region.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The highest frequencies are reached by a few tens of variants present at >70% (and a few thousands at >50%) in Africa, the Americas, and Oceania.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Within a population, SNPs can be assigned a minor allele frequency (MAF)—the lowest allele frequency at a locus that is observed in a particular population.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This is simply the lesser of the two allele frequencies for single-nucleotide polymorphisms.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] With this knowledge, scientists have developed new methods in analyzing population structures in less studied species.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] By using pooling techniques, the cost of the analysis is significantly lowered.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] These techniques are based on sequencing a population in a pooled sample instead of sequencing every individual within the population by itself.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] With new bioinformatics tools, there is a possibility of investigating population structure, gene flow, and gene migration by observing the allele frequencies within the entire population.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] With these protocols there is a possibility for combining the advantages of SNPs with micro satellite markers.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] However, there is information lost in the process, such as linkage disequilibrium and zygosity information.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Single nucleotide polymorphisms serve as powerful molecular markers in contemporary genetic research and clinical practice.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Association studies, particularly genome-wide association studies (GWAS), represent the primary application of SNP technology for identifying genetic variants linked to human diseases and traits.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The development of tag SNP methodology has significantly enhanced the efficiency of genomic studies by exploiting patterns of linkage disequilibrium across the human genome.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Tag SNPs function as representative markers that capture genetic variation within specific chromosomal regions, allowing researchers to survey large genomic areas without genotyping every individual variant.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This approach reduces both the financial cost and computational burden of large-scale genetic studies while maintaining sufficient power to detect disease-associated loci.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The selection of optimal tag SNPs relies on sophisticated algorithms that identify markers capable of capturing the maximum amount of genetic information within defined genomic intervals.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Haplotype reconstruction represents another fundamental application where SNPs enable the characterization of inherited genetic blocks.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Researchers utilize dense SNP maps to identify and analyze haplotype structures, which consist of sets of closely linked alleles that tend to be transmitted together through generations.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] These haplotype patterns provide insights into population history, demographic events, and evolutionary processes that have shaped contemporary genetic diversity.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The International HapMap Project exemplified this application by creating comprehensive maps of common haplotype patterns across diverse human populations.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Linkage disequilibrium analysis forms the theoretical foundation for many SNP-based applications in population genetics and disease mapping.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This phenomenon describes the non-random association of alleles at different genomic positions, which occurs when variants are inherited together more frequently than would be expected by chance alone.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The extent of linkage disequilibrium between SNPs depends primarily on physical distance along chromosomes and local recombination rates, with closer variants generally showing stronger associations.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Understanding these patterns enables researchers to predict which SNPs will provide redundant information and guides the selection of informative markers for association studies.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] In genetic epidemiology, SNPs have emerged as essential tools for investigating disease transmission patterns and population structure.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Whole-genome sequencing approaches utilize SNP variation to define transmission clusters in infectious disease outbreaks, where cases showing similar genetic profiles may represent linked transmission events.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This application has proven particularly valuable for tuberculosis surveillance and contact tracing, where traditional epidemiological methods may fail to identify all transmission links.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Additionally, SNP-based analyses contribute to understanding population stratification and ancestry, which are crucial factors in designing appropriate study controls and interpreting association results across diverse ethnic groups.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Variations in the DNA sequences of humans can affect how humans develop diseases and respond to pathogens, chemicals, drugs, vaccines, and other agents.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs are also critical for personalized medicine.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Examples include biomedical research, forensics, pharmacogenetics, and disease causation, as outlined below.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] One of the main contributions of SNPs in clinical research is genome-wide association study (GWAS).
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Genome-wide genetic data can be generated by multiple technologies, including SNP array and whole genome sequencing.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] GWAS has been commonly used in identifying SNPs associated with diseases or clinical phenotypes or traits.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Since GWAS is a genome-wide assessment, a large sample site is required to obtain sufficient statistical power to detect all possible associations.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Some SNPs have relatively small effect on diseases or clinical phenotypes or traits.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] To estimate study power, the genetic model for disease needs to be considered, such as dominant, recessive, or additive effects.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Due to genetic heterogeneity, GWAS analysis must be adjusted for race.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Candidate gene association study is commonly used in genetic study before the invention of high throughput genotyping or sequencing technologies.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Candidate gene association study is to investigate limited number of pre-specified SNPs for association with diseases or clinical phenotypes or traits.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] So this is a hypothesis driven approach.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Since only a limited number of SNPs are tested, a relatively small sample size is sufficient to detect the association.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Candidate gene association approach is also commonly used to confirm findings from GWAS in independent samples.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Genome-wide SNP data can be used for homozygosity mapping.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Homozygosity mapping is a method used to identify homozygous autosomal recessive loci, which can be a powerful tool to map genomic regions or genes that are involved in disease pathogenesis.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Recently, preliminary results reported SNPs as important components of the epigenetic program in organisms.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Moreover, cosmopolitan studies in European and South Asiatic populations have revealed the influence of SNPs in the methylation of specific CpG sites.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] In addition, meQTL enrichment analysis using GWAS database, demonstrated that those associations are important toward the prediction of biological traits.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs have historically been used to match a forensic DNA sample to a suspect but has been made obsolete due to advancing STR-based DNA fingerprinting techniques.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] However, the development of next-generation-sequencing (NGS) technology may allow for more opportunities for the use of SNPs in phenotypic clues such as ethnicity, hair color, and eye color with a good probability of a match.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This can additionally be applied to increase the accuracy of facial reconstructions by providing information that may otherwise be unknown, and this information can be used to help identify suspects even without a STR DNA profile match.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Some cons to using SNPs versus STRs is that SNPs yield less information than STRs, and therefore more SNPs are needed for analysis before a profile of a suspect is able to be created.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Additionally, SNPs heavily rely on the presence of a database for comparative analysis of samples.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] However, in instances with degraded or small volume samples, SNP techniques are an excellent alternative to STR methods.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs (as opposed to STRs) have an abundance of potential markers, can be fully automated, and a possible reduction of required fragment length to less than 100 bp.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Pharmacogenetics focuses on identifying genetic variations including SNPs associated with differential responses to treatment.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Many drug metabolizing enzymes, drug targets, or target pathways can be influenced by SNPs.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The SNPs involved in drug metabolizing enzyme activities can change drug pharmacokinetics, while the SNPs involved in drug target or its pathway can change drug pharmacodynamics.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Therefore, SNPs are potential genetic markers that can be used to predict drug exposure or effectiveness of the treatment.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Genome-wide pharmacogenetic study is called pharmacogenomics.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Pharmacogenetics and pharmacogenomics are important in the development of precision medicine, especially for life-threatening diseases such as cancers.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Only small amount of SNPs in the human genome may have impact on human diseases.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Large scale GWAS has been done for the most important human diseases, including heart diseases, metabolic diseases, autoimmune diseases, and neurodegenerative and psychiatric disorders.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Most of the SNPs with relatively large effects on these diseases have been identified.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] These findings have significantly improved understanding of disease pathogenesis and molecular pathways, and facilitated development of better treatment.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Further GWAS with larger samples size will reveal the SNPs with relatively small effect on diseases.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] For common and complex diseases, such as type-2 diabetes, rheumatoid arthritis, and Alzheimer's disease, multiple genetic factors are involved in disease etiology.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] In addition, gene-gene interaction and gene-environment interaction also play an important role in disease initiation and progression.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] As there are for genes, bioinformatics databases exist for SNPs.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The International SNP Map working group mapped the sequence flanking each SNP by alignment to the genomic sequence of large-insert clones in Genebank.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] These alignments were converted to chromosomal coordinates that is shown in Table 1.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] This list has greatly increased since, with, for instance, the Kaviar database now listing 162 million single nucleotide variants.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The nomenclature for SNPs include several variations for an individual SNP, while lacking a common consensus.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The rs### standard is that which has been adopted by dbSNP and uses the prefix "rs", for "reference SNP", followed by a unique and arbitrary number.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs are frequently referred to by their dbSNP rs number, as in the examples above.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The Human Genome Variation Society (HGVS) uses a standard which conveys more information about the SNP.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The first section is usually a chromosome or mRNA identifier, such as NC_000023.10 (DNA) or NM_004006.3 (mRNA).
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] The type of change is denoted by a string.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] SNPs can be easily assayed due to only containing two possible alleles and three possible genotypes involving the two alleles: homozygous A, homozygous B and heterozygous AB, leading to many possible techniques for analysis.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Some include: DNA sequencing; capillary electrophoresis; mass spectrometry; single-strand conformation polymorphism (SSCP); single base extension; electrochemical analysis; denaturating HPLC and gel electrophoresis; restriction fragment length polymorphism; and hybridization analysis.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] An important group of SNPs are those that corresponds to missense mutations causing amino acid change on protein level.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Point mutation of particular residue can have different effect on protein function (from no effect to complete disruption its function).
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Usually, change in amino acids with similar size and physico-chemical properties (e.g. substitution from leucine to valine) has mild effect, and opposite.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/single-nucleotide-polymorphism] Similarly, if SNP disrupts secondary structure elements (e.g. substitution to proline in alpha helix region) such mutation usually may affect whole protein structure and function.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Most NGS based methods for SNV detection are designed to detect germline variations in the individual's genome.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] These are the mutations that an individual biologically inherits from their parents, and are the usual type of variants searched for when performing such analysis (except for certain specific applications where somatic mutations are sought).
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Very often, the searched for variants occur with some (possibly rare) frequency, throughout the population, in which case they may be referred to as single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs).
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Technically the term SNP only refers to these kinds of variations, however in practice they are often used synonymously with SNV in the literature on variant calling.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] In addition, since the detection of germline SNVs requires determining the individual's genotype at each locus, the phrase "SNP genotyping" may also be used to refer to this process.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] However this phrase may also refer to wet-lab experimental procedures for classifying genotypes at a set of known SNP locations.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] SNP annotation to predict the functional effect of each variation.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] The usual output of these procedures is a VCF file.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] However, when working with real NGS data this sort of naive approach is not used, as it cannot account for the noise in the input data.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] The nucleotide counts used for base calling contain errors and bias, both due do the sequenced reads themselves, and the alignment process.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] This issue can be mitigated to some extent by sequencing to a greater depth of read coverage, however this is often expensive, and many practical studies require making inferences on low coverage data.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Probabilistic methods aim to overcome the above issue, by producing robust estimates of the probabilities of each of the possible genotypes, taking into account noise, as well as other available prior information that can be used to improve estimates.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] A genotype can then be predicted based on these probabilities, often according to the MAP estimate.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Probabilistic methods for variant calling are based on Bayes' theorem.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] In the context of variant calling, Bayes' theorem defines the probability of each genotype being the true genotype given the observed data, in terms of the prior probabilities of each possible genotype, and the probability distribution of the data given each possible genotype.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] The calculation of prior probabilities depends on available data from the genome being studied, and the type of analysis being performed.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] For studies where good reference data containing frequencies of known mutations is available (for example, in studying human genome data), these known frequencies of genotypes in the population can be used to estimate priors.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Given population wide allele frequencies, prior genotype probabilities can be calculated at each locus according to the Hardy–Weinberg equilibrium.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] In the absence of such data, constant priors can be used, independent of the locus.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] These can be set using heuristically chosen values, possibly informed by the kind of variations being sought by the study.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Alternatively, supervised machine-learning procedures have been investigated that seek to learn optimal prior values for individuals in a sample, using supplied NGS data from these individuals.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] The error model used in creating a probabilistic method for variant calling is the basis for calculating the $P(D\mid G)$ term used in Bayes' theorem.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] However, in presence of noise in the read data this assumption is violated, and the $P(D\mid G)$ values need to account for the possibility that erroneous nucleotides are present in the aligned reads at each locus.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] However more sophisticated procedures are available which attempt to more realistically replicate the actual error patterns observed in real data in calculating the conditional data probabilities.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] For instance, estimations of read quality (measured as Phred quality scores) have been incorporated in these calculations, taking into account the expected error rate in each individual read at a locus.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Another technique that has successfully been incorporated into error models is base quality recalibration, where separate error rates are calculated – based on prior known information about error patterns – for each possible nucleotide substitution.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Research shows that each possible nucleotide substitution is not equally likely to show up as an error in sequencing data, and so base quality recalibration has been applied to improve error probability estimates.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] In the above discussion, it has been assumed that the genotype probabilities at each locus are calculated independently; that is, the entire genotype is partitioned into independent genotypes at each locus, whose probabilities are calculated independently.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] However, due to linkage disequilibrium the genotypes of nearby loci are in general not independent.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] As a result, partitioning the overall genotype instead into a sequence of overlapping haplotypes allows these correlations to be modelled, resulting in more precise probability estimates through the incorporation of population-wide haplotype frequencies in the prior.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] The use of haplotypes to improve variant detection accuracy has been applied successfully, for instance in the 1000 Genomes Project.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] As an alternative to probabilistic methods, heuristic methods exist for performing variant calling on NGS data.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Instead of modelling the distribution of the observed data and using Bayesian statistics to calculate genotype probabilities, variant calls are made based on a variety of heuristic factors, such as minimum allele counts, read quality cut-offs, bounds on read depth, etc.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Although they have been relatively unpopular in practice in comparison to probabilistic methods, in practice due to their use of bounds and cut-offs they can be robust to outlying data that violate the assumptions of probabilistic models.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] An important part of the design of variant calling methods using NGS data is the DNA sequence used as a reference to which the NGS reads are aligned.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] In human genetics studies, high quality references are available, from sources such as the HapMap project, which can substantially improve the accuracy of the variant calls made by variant calling algorithms.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] As a bonus, such references can be a source of prior genotype probabilities for Bayesian-based analysis.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] However, in the absence of such a high quality reference, experimentally obtained reads can first be assembled in order to create a reference sequence for alignment.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Various methods exist for filtering data in variant calling experiments, in order to remove sources of error/bias.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] This can involve the removal of suspicious reads before performing alignment and/or filtering of the list of variants returned by the variant calling algorithm.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Depending on the sequencing platform used, various biases may exist within the set of sequenced reads.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] For instance, strand bias can occur, where there is a highly unequal distribution of forward vs reverse directions in the reads aligned in some neighborhood.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Additionally, there may occur an unusually high duplication of some reads (for instance due to bias in PCR).
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] In addition to methods that align reads from individual sample(s) to a reference genome in order to detect germline genetic variants, reads from multiple tissue samples within a single individual can be aligned and compared in order to detect somatic variants.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] These variants correspond to mutations that have occurred de novo within groups of somatic cells within an individual (that is, they are not present within the individual's germline cells).
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] This form of analysis has been frequently applied to the study of cancer, where many studies are designed around investigating the profile of somatic mutations within cancerous tissues.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Until recently, software tools for carrying out this form of analysis have been heavily underdeveloped, and were based on the same algorithms used to detect germline variations.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] Such procedures are not optimized for this task, because they do not adequately model the statistical correlation between the genotypes present in multiple tissue samples from the same individual.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] More recent investigations have resulted in the development of software tools especially optimized for the detection of somatic mutations from multiple tissue samples.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/snv-calling-from-ngs-data] In addition there has recently been some investigation in machine learning based techniques for performing this analysis.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] The **Variant Call Format** or **VCF** is a standard text file format used in bioinformatics for storing gene sequence or DNA sequence variations.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] The format was developed in 2010 for the 1000 Genomes Project and has since been used by other large-scale genotyping and DNA sequencing projects.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] VCF is a common output format for variant calling programs due to its relative simplicity and scalability.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] Many tools have been developed for editing and manipulating VCF files, including VCFtools, which was released in conjunction with the VCF format in 2011, and BCFtools, which was included as part of SAMtools until being split into an independent package in 2014.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] The standard is currently in version 4.5, although the 1000 Genomes Project has developed its own specification for structural variations such as duplications, which are not easily accommodated into the existing schema.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] Additional file formats have been developed based on VCF, including **genomic VCF** (**gVCF**). gVCF is an extended format which includes additional information about "blocks" that match the reference and their qualities.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] The header begins the file and provides metadata describing the body of the file.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] Header lines are denoted as starting with #.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] Special keywords in the header are denoted with ##.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] Recommended keywords include fileformat, fileDate and reference.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] The header contains keywords that optionally semantically and syntactically describe the fields used in the body of the file, notably INFO, FILTER, and FORMAT (see below).
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] In practice, VCF headers often contain substantial metadata added by upstream software, such as reference genome information, contig definitions, filter descriptions, sample declarations, provenance fields, and custom INFO or FORMAT tags.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] This metadata is important for validation and interpretation.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] The body of VCF follows the header, and is tab separated into 8 mandatory columns and an unlimited number of optional columns that may be used to record other information about the sample(s).
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] When additional columns are used, the first optional column is used to describe the format of the data in the columns that follow.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] Any other info fields are defined in the .vcf header.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] Any other format fields are defined in the .vcf header.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] Binary VCF or BCF files are binary, BGZF compressed variation of VCF files.
[src:variant-calling-gatk/variant-call-format] BCF files allow fast and efficient indexed queries through tools like Tabix once an index file has been created.
